We cannot too often and too clearly repeat to ourselves that that worst sin, pharisaism, is innate and always committed in obedience to a conscience bred upon sacred lore and traditions as interpreted by some canon contrary to God's universal love.

In this connection an analysis of the denunciations of the Pharisees spoken by our Lord and by St. Paul is interesting. The contentiori of Jesus certainly was not that the Pharisees did not try to keep the law, nor when St. Paul took up the same theme, as, for example, in the second chapter of the Epistle to the Romans, did he suppose that the man who was instructed in the law was the less prone to keep it; the argument evidently is that if the position is one of such boasted privilege, the life should be superior to the common failure of good men who are without the privilege ;
